        {
            "title": "AraMiS",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 1,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2007
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 1,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2007
                }
            },
            "description": "The AraMiS project led to the development of a modular architecture for nano-satellites. The basic idea was based on smart sub-systems that could be plugged with each other to create a basic satellite. Basic modules could be combined together to improve performances (like coping with an additional solar panel) and provide graceful failure tolerance. My task was the architectural design and the development of the solar panel power conversion module.",
            "contributors": [
                {
                    "type": "standardizedContributor",
                    "first_name": "Stefano",
                    "last_name": "Speretta",
                    "name": null,
                    "headline": "Assistant Professor at Technische Universiteit Delft"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "PiCPoT",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 4,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2004
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 4,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2006
                }
            },
            "description": "The PiCPoT project led to the development of a nanosatellite completely built by students of several engineering departments. The main constraint of this project was its cost, so every system was built using Commercial Off-The-Shelf (COTS) components and radiation-hardened by design techniques to ensure survival in space. Since most components could have been prone to latch-up, particular attention had been focused on creating a protection system that monitors the supply current of all systems. The main goals of this satellite are the transmission of on-board telemetry measures and photos taken with commercial cameras. I was involved in the final integration and testing campaign, getting to know how all the sub-systems were interacting with each other and how to ensure everything was working as designed.",
